      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The word for “linen cloth,” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Sindôn,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " points, according to different derivations, to a Sidonian or an Indian fabric. It was probably of the nature of muslin rather than linen, and seems to have been specially used by the Egyptians for folding round their mummies, but sometimes also for the sheet in which a man slept (Herod. ii. 82, 95). In the New Testament it appears only in the account of our Lord’s burial and in the strange narrative of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 14:51",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
