  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And when Joseph had taken the body,.... Down from the cross, with the assistance of others, or from the hands of those who had orders to deliver it to him: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "he wrapped it in a clean linen cloth: that is, he wound up the body in it round and round, as was the custom of the Jews; see Acts 5:6. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "he wrapped it in a clean linen cloth: that is, he wound up the body in it round and round, as was the custom of the Jews; see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 5:6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "John 11:44. Nor was it usual to bury in any thing but linen: so it is said (m), ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 11:44",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". Nor was it usual to bury in any thing but linen: so it is said (m), ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "\"let the wrappings, or grave clothes, be  , \"of white linen\"; and let not the price of them be dear, for it is forbidden to bury in wrappings of silk, or broidered garments, even to a prince of Israel: for this is pride and destruction, and the work of the Gentiles. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "This clean linen cloth, in which the dead body of Christ was wrapped, may be an emblem of his purity and innocence, who did no sin; nor did he die for any of his own, but for the sins of others; and also of his pure and spotless righteousness, which is compared to fine linen, clean and white, and which he now had wrought out, and brought in; see Revelation 19:8. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "This clean linen cloth, in which the dead body of Christ was wrapped, may be an emblem of his purity and innocence, who did no sin; nor did he die for any of his own, but for the sins of others; and also of his pure and spotless righteousness, which is compared to fine linen, clean and white, and which he now had wrought out, and brought in; see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Revelation 19:8",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(m) Juchasin, fol. 54. 2. Vid. Maimon. Hilchot Ebel, c. 4. sect. 2.",
        "children": [
          {
